        <!-- Eligibility requirements -->
        <section id="eligibility" class="content-section">
          <h2>Eligibility Requirements</h2>
          <p>Both the petitioner and the foreign spouse must meet specific requirements. Failing any of these can result in denial:</p>

          <div class="eligibility-grid">
            <div class="elig-col">
              <div class="elig-header elig-petitioner">
                <span>🇺🇸</span> <h3>Petitioner Must:</h3>
              </div>
              <div class="elig-items">
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Be a U.S. citizen (or LPR for CR-1/AOS, with longer wait)</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Be legally free to marry (no current undissolved marriage)</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Meet the income requirement: 125% of federal poverty guideline</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Have no disqualifying criminal history (especially offenses against minors)</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Sign the I-864 Affidavit of Support (legally binding)</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="elig-col">
              <div class="elig-header elig-beneficiary">
                <span>🌍</span> <h3>Beneficiary Must:</h3>
              </div>
              <div class="elig-items">
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Be legally free to marry</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Not be inadmissible (criminal grounds, health, fraud, prior bars)</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Have a valid passport</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Pass the medical exam</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-yes">
                  <span class="ei-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>Be in a bona fide (genuine) marriage — not for immigration purposes</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-no">
                  <span class="ei-icon ei-no">✗</span>
                  <div><strong>Prior immigration fraud</strong> — permanent bar unless waived</div>
                </div>
                <div class="elig-item elig-no">
                  <span class="ei-icon ei-no">✗</span>
                  <div><strong>Entered without inspection (EWI)</strong> — usually cannot adjust status inside U.S.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- What happens after green card -->
        <section id="after-greencard" class="content-section">
          <h2>After the Green Card — Conditions, I-751, and Citizenship</h2>

          <p>If the marriage was less than 2 years old when the green card was granted, you receive a <strong>conditional</strong> green card (CR-1 code). The conditions are removed after 2 years by filing Form I-751. If the marriage was 2+ years old, you receive a 10-year green card (IR-1) immediately — no I-751 needed.</p>

          <div class="after-path">
            <div class="ap-step">
              <div class="ap-icon">🟢</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Conditional green card (CR-1) — Year 0</strong>
                <p>2-year card. Live and work anywhere in the U.S. Maintain lawful status.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="ap-arrow">↓</div>
            <div class="ap-step ap-step-highlight">
              <div class="ap-icon">📋</div>
              <div>
                <strong>File I-751 — Month 21–24</strong>
                <p>Remove conditions with evidence of ongoing bona fide marriage. Processing: 24–36 months. Automatic 18-month extension of status on filing.</p>
                <SmartLink href="/i-751-petition-remove-conditions" class="ap-link">I-751 complete guide →</SmartLink>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="ap-arrow">↓</div>
            <div class="ap-step">
              <div class="ap-icon">🪪</div>
              <div>
                <strong>10-year green card (IR-1) — ~Year 4–5</strong>
                <p>Full permanent resident. Renewable every 10 years. No further conditions.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="ap-arrow">↓</div>
            <div class="ap-step ap-step-gold">
              <div class="ap-icon">🇺🇸</div>
              <div>
                <strong>U.S. citizenship — Year 3 from green card</strong>
                <p>Spouses of U.S. citizens can naturalize after just 3 years of LPR status. File Form N-400, pass civics test and interview, take the oath.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

