        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section id="faq" class="content-section">
          <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="faq-list">
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>How long does it take to get a green card through marriage?</summary>
              <p>It depends on your path. Adjustment of Status (inside U.S.): 12–24 months. CR-1 spousal visa (abroad, already married): 18–36 months. K-1 fiancé visa + AOS (not yet married, abroad): 24–42 months total. These are end-to-end estimates — actual times vary by USCIS service center, embassy, and individual case complexity.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Can I get a green card if I married a U.S. citizen while abroad?</summary>
              <p>Yes — the CR-1 spousal visa is designed exactly for this situation. The U.S. citizen files I-130 from the U.S., USCIS approves it, and the NVC schedules a consular interview at the U.S. embassy in the foreign spouse's home country. The foreign spouse enters the U.S. directly as a conditional permanent resident.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What's the difference between K-1 and CR-1?</summary>
              <p>K-1 is for unmarried couples — you enter the U.S. on a K-1 visa, marry within 90 days, then file for Adjustment of Status. Two processes, but faster initial U.S. entry. CR-1 is for married couples — the foreign spouse enters directly as a conditional permanent resident. One process, but slower overall. The CR-1 is generally more cost-efficient; the K-1 gets the couple together sooner.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>How much does a green card through marriage cost?</summary>
              <p>Government fees alone: K-1 + AOS ~$3,285; CR-1 ~$1,970; AOS inside U.S. ~$2,190. Add $200–$500 for medical exams, $100–$400 for translations, and $1,500–$5,000+ for an immigration attorney if you use one. Total realistic range: $3,500–$9,000+ depending on path and whether you use professional help.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Does marrying a U.S. citizen guarantee a green card?</summary>
              <p>No. It makes you an immediate relative (no visa backlog), but you must still prove the marriage is genuine, pass background checks, meet health requirements, and complete the full application process. Attempting a fraudulent marriage for immigration purposes is a federal crime punishable by prison time and permanent inadmissibility.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Can I get a green card through marriage if I'm undocumented?</summary>
              <p>It depends on how you entered. If you entered legally and overstayed, you may be able to adjust status inside the U.S. after marrying a citizen. If you entered without inspection (crossed the border without a visa), Adjustment of Status is generally unavailable and departure can trigger a 3- or 10-year bar. Consult an immigration attorney before taking any action — this situation requires professional guidance.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </section>

